<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=370&amp;p=2842#p2842</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=370&amp;p=2842#p2842"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[UNIF database?]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=370&amp;p=2842#p2842"><![CDATA[
That is correct - the UNIF "MIRR" blocks is <strong>ONLY</strong> relevant if the board (described in the "MAPR" block) has solder pads on it to select hardwired mirroring. Many [non-Nintendo] cartridges are simply hardwired to horizontal or vertical mirroring (in which case the board name would imply it), while there are also a few Nintendo boards (MMC3, possibly MMC1 as well) which have solder pads to select between Horizontal, Vertical, and Mapper-controlled.<br /><br />The fact that there are <em>two</em> different "hard-wired single-screen" settings in UNIF is rather stupid, since if it's hard-wired you'll NEVER be able to tell which half you're using.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=7">Quietust</a> — Sun Jul 17, 2005 9:14 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
